      (c)    Contractors, if not accompanied by a KAAPA employee, may be given a radio to communicate critical or emergency situations in the event one arises.  This will be determined during project planning, pre-job briefing, or heightened security risk.

      (d)    If an evacuation is required, control room board operator will collect check /sign in ledger, located in control room as a means of identifying contractors on site.  Administrative office will collect check/sign in ledger and gather at the safe gathering location.  A role call will occur, in the event someone is presumed to be missing, attempts will be made through radio communication.  If unsuccessful, wait for emergency services to arrive before reentering the facility.



Spill Prevention Control & Countermeasure/Facility Response Plan

EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTION PLAN (ERAP)



This ERAP contains a summary of facility information pertinent to responding to a release at the facility.



The standard response in the event of a spill involves:

Secure area to prevent ignition sources;

Reduce or stop the leak if it can be done easily, and at little risk to personnel (i.e. close a valve);

Notify the site personnel and spill response contractor as necessary, see Table 2;

Control spread of oil to sensitive environments, see Table 3;

Initiate recovery of oil by excavation of contaminated soil or pumping of liquids as appropriate, see     Table 3;

Complete a discharge notification checklist (follows) and initiate spill notification requirements as necessary, reference Tables 4 and 5 for contact information and notification scenarios.

